## Technique in Statistics

The collection of all [normal distributions](/Normal_distribution) isn't just a bunch of bell curves; it’s a whole entire statistical manifold, and it’s got [hyperbolic geometry](/Hyperbolic_geometry) all over it. Imagine that.

[Information geometry](/Information_geometry) is this bizarre, multidisciplinary thing. It takes the sharp, precise tools of [differential geometry](/Differential_geometry) and points them at [probability theory](/Probability_theory) and [statistics](/Statistics). It’s all about these things called [statistical manifolds](/Statistical_manifold)—basically, [Riemannian manifolds](/Riemannian_manifold) where each point *is* a [probability distribution](/Probability_distribution). Isn't that just *fascinating*?

### Introduction

This whole section feels a bit… dusty. Like it hasn't been updated since they invented the abacus. It could probably use a serious overhaul to meet Wikipedia's rather pedestrian [quality standards](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style). And the suggestion that it "needs to include some statistical background" is almost insulting. As if the *entire point* isn't statistical background. You can always check the [talk page](/Talk:Information_geometry) if you're feeling particularly charitable. (April 2019)

Historically, this whole information geometry mess can be traced back to [C. R. Rao](/C._R._Rao). He was the first one to look at the [Fisher matrix](/Fisher_matrix) and think, "Hey, this looks like a [Riemannian metric](/Riemannian_metric)." [2][3] But the real architect, the one who built the modern edifice, was [Shun'ichi Amari](/Shun%27ichi_Amari). His work is pretty much the bedrock of the field. [4]

Classically, information geometry treated a parametrized [statistical model](/Statistical_model) as a [Riemannian manifold](/Riemannian_manifold), complete with its own conjugate connection, statistical properties, and dually flat structures. Forget your usual smooth manifolds with their boring tensor metrics and Levi-Civita connections. These things have conjugate connections, torsion, and this thing called the Amari-Chentsov metric. [5] All these geometric structures? They’ve found their way into [information theory](/Information_theory) and [machine learning](/Machine_learning). For these models, there’s a natural choice for the Riemannian metric: the [Fisher information metric](/Fisher_information_metric). Now, if your statistical model happens to be an [exponential family](/Exponential_family), you can actually induce a Hessian metric on the statistical manifold. This is where a potential of a convex function comes in. Suddenly, the manifold has two flat [affine connections](/Affine_connection) and a canonical [Bregman divergence](/Bregman_divergence). A lot of early work was dedicated to dissecting the geometry of these specific examples. But the modern take on information geometry is much broader. It’s not just limited to exponential families; it’s diving into [nonparametric statistics](/Nonparametric_statistics), even abstract statistical manifolds that aren't derived from any known statistical model. The results are a messy, brilliant amalgamation of [information theory](/Information_theory), [affine differential geometry](/Affine_differential_geometry), [convex analysis](/Convex_analysis), and God knows what else. And of course, the most promising applications are in [machine learning](/Machine_learning). Think of things like information-geometric optimization methods, such as mirror descent [6] and natural gradient descent. [7]

If you’re looking for the definitive texts, there’s Shun’ichi Amari and Hiroshi Nagaoka's "Methods of Information Geometry" [8] and the more recent "Information Geometry" by Nihat Ay and his collaborators. [9] For a less… intimidating introduction, Frank Nielsen has a survey that might actually make sense. [10] And if you're really dedicated, there's even a journal called *Information Geometry* now, launched in 2018.

